{"title_page": "Maurice Bardonneau", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name=\n|image=Maurice Bardonneau.jpg\n| image_size     = 260px\n|caption=\n|birth_date=22 May 1885\n|birth_place=[[Saint-Maurice, Val-de-Marne]], France\n|death_date=3 July 1958 (aged 73)\n|death_place=[[Issy-les-Moulineaux]], France\n| height = \n| weight = \n|sport=Cycling\n|club=Association V\u00e9locip\u00e9dique d'Amateurs\n|alma_mater=\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{FRA}}}}\n{{MedalOlympics}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1906 Intercalated Games|1906 Athens]]|[[Cycling at the 1906 Intercalated Games|Road race]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1906 Intercalated Games|1906 Athens]]|[[Cycling at the 1906 Intercalated Games|20 km]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Motor-paced World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|1906 Geneva|Amateurs}}\n}}\n'''Maurice Charles Adolphe Bardonneau''' (22 May 1885 \u2013 3 July 1958) was a French cyclist. He competed at the [[1906 Summer Olympics]] (Intercalated Games) in the 5&nbsp;km, 20&nbsp;km and road race and won two silver medals in the last two events.<ref name=r3/> In the same year he also won the [[UCI Motor-paced World Championships]] and the first stage of the [[Paris\u2013Brussels]] road race.<ref name=r1/><ref name=r2/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[http://www.radsportseiten.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=12378 Maurice Bardonneau]. radsportseiten.net</ref>\n<ref name=r2>[http://www.bikecult.com/bikecultbook/sports_trackWorlds.html Track Cycling World Championships 2012 to 1893]. bikecult.com</ref>\n<ref name=r3>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/maurice-bardonneau-1.html Maurice Bardonneau]. sports-reference.com</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bardonneau, Maurice}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1906 Intercalated Games]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cr\u00e9teil]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1906 Intercalated Games]]\n\n\n{{cycling-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n|name=\n|image=Maurice Bardonneau.jpg\n| image_size     = 260px\n|caption=\n|birth_date=22 May 1885\n|birth_place=[[Saint-Maurice, Val-de-Marne]], France\n|death_date=3 July 1958 (aged 73)\n|death_place=[[Issy-les-Moulineaux]], France\n| height = \n| weight = \n|sport=Cycling\n|club=Association V\u00e9locip\u00e9dique d'Amateurs\n|alma_mater=\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry| {{FRA}}}}\n{{MedalOlympics}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1906 Intercalated Games|1906 Athens]]|[[Cycling at the 1906 Intercalated Games|Road race]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1906 Intercalated Games|1906 Athens]]|[[Cycling at the 1906 Intercalated Games|20 km]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Motor-paced World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|1906 Geneva|Amateurs}}\n}}\n'''Maurice Charles Adolphe Bardonneau''' (22 May 1885 \u2013 3 July 1958) was a French cyclist. He competed at the [[1906 Summer Olympics]] (Intercalated Games) in the 5&nbsp;km, 20&nbsp;km and road race and won two silver medals in the last two events.<ref name=r3/> In the same year he also won the [[UCI Motor-paced World Championships]] and the first stage of the [[Paris\u2013Brussels]] road race.<ref name=r1/><ref name=r2/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=r1>[http://www.radsportseiten.net/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=12378 Maurice Bardonneau]. radsportseiten.net</ref>\n<ref name=r2>[http://www.bikecult.com/bikecultbook/sports_trackWorlds.html Track Cycling World Championships 2012 to 1893]. bikecult.com</ref>\n<ref name=r3>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ba/maurice-bardonneau-1.html Maurice Bardonneau]. sports-reference.com</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bardonneau, Maurice}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1906 Intercalated Games]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cr\u00e9teil]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1906 Intercalated Games]]\n\n\n{{cycling-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_Bardonneau"}
{"title_page": "Maurice Archambaud", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Maurice Archambaud\n| image         = \n| full_name     = Maurice Archambaud\n| nickname      = Le Nabot\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1906|08|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1955|12|03|1906|08|30}}\n| death_place   = [[Le Raincy]], France\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = 10 stages Tour de France<br/>Paris\u2013Nice (1939)\n}}\n\n'''Maurice Archambaud''' (30 August 1906 in [[Paris]] \u2013 3 December 1955 in [[Le Raincy]]<ref name=\"velo-club.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.velo-club.net/article.php?sid=15616 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205181238/http://www.velo-club.net/article.php?sid=15616 |archivedate=2008-12-05 }}</ref>) was a [[France|French]] professional cyclist from 1932 to 1944. His short stature earned him the [[nickname]] of ''le nabot'', or \"the dwarf\", but his colossal thighs made him an exceptional rider.\n\nHe won Paris-Soissons and Paris-Verneuil as an amateur in 1931 and turned professional the following year for [[Alcyon]], one of the top teams in France. He won the inaugural [[Grand Prix des Nations]] in his first season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wielerdagboek.be/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817024903/http://www.wielerdagboek.be/ |archivedate=2008-08-17 }}</ref>\n\nHe set the world [[hour record]] at 45.767&nbsp;km at the Vigorelli [[velodrome]] in [[Milan]] on 3 November 1937.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/ritfiche.php?ritid=36019 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003143137/http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/ritfiche.php?ritid=36019 |archivedate=2012-10-03 }}</ref> He beat the Dutchman, [[Frans Slaats]]' record of 45.485&nbsp;km, set on 29 September 1937.<ref>Match, France, issue 599, 9 November 1937</ref> The record stood for five years before being beaten by [[Fausto Coppi]].\n\nArchambaud rode for France in the [[Tour de France]] between the wars. His sudden changes of form and frequent falls meant that he never won the race, but he did win nine stages<ref name=\"velo-club.net\"/>  and wear the [[yellow jersey]].\n\nHe won a shorter stage race, [[Paris\u2013Nice]], in 1936 and 1939.<ref>http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/cy/profiles/2357.html</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1932\n: [[Grand Prix des Nations]]: winner\n;1933\n: [[1933 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n:: Winner stages 1 and 11\n:: 5th overall\n:: 9 days in the [[yellow jersey]]\n;1935\n: [[1935 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stages 5A and 14B\n::7th overall\n: [[1935 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n:: Winner stage 14B\n: Paris-Caen\n: [[Six-day racing|Six days]] of Paris\n:GP de l'Echo d'Alger\n;1936\n: [[1936 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 4\n::5 days in the yellow jersey.\n: [[Paris\u2013Nice]]\n;1937\n: [[1937 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 2\n: [[Hour record]]\n: [[Giro della provincia Milano]] (with [[Aldo Bini]])\n;1939\n: [[1939 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n:: Winner stages 10B, 10C, 12B and 17B\n: [[Paris\u2013Nice]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cycling Archives|282}}\n*{{Tour de France results|2638|archive=20070807135513}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frans Slaats]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Hour record|UCI hour record]] (45.767 km)| years = 3 November 1937-7 November 1942}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Fausto Coppi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Archambaud, Maurice}}\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:French Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:French Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Maurice Archambaud\n| image         = \n| full_name     = Maurice Archambaud\n| nickname      = Le Nabot\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1906|08|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1955|12|03|1906|08|30}}\n| death_place   = [[Le Raincy]], France\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = 10 stages Tour de France<br/>Paris\u2013Nice (1939)\n}}\n\n'''Maurice Archambaud''' (30 August 1906 in [[Paris]] \u2013 3 December 1955 in [[Le Raincy]]<ref name=\"velo-club.net\">{{cite web |url=http://www.velo-club.net/article.php?sid=15616 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205181238/http://www.velo-club.net/article.php?sid=15616 |archivedate=2008-12-05 }}</ref>) was a [[France|French]] professional cyclist from 1932 to 1944. His short stature earned him the [[nickname]] of ''le nabot'', or \"the dwarf\", but his colossal thighs made him an exceptional rider.\n\nHe won Paris-Soissons and Paris-Verneuil as an amateur in 1931 and turned professional the following year for [[Alcyon]], one of the top teams in France. He won the inaugural [[Grand Prix des Nations]] in his first season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wielerdagboek.be/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817024903/http://www.wielerdagboek.be/ |archivedate=2008-08-17 }}</ref>\n\nHe set the world [[hour record]] at 45.767&nbsp;km at the Vigorelli [[velodrome]] in [[Milan]] on 3 November 1937.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/ritfiche.php?ritid=36019 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003143137/http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/ritfiche.php?ritid=36019 |archivedate=2012-10-03 }}</ref> He beat the Dutchman, [[Frans Slaats]]' record of 45.485&nbsp;km, set on 29 September 1937.<ref>Match, France, issue 599, 9 November 1937</ref> The record stood for five years before being beaten by [[Fausto Coppi]].\n\nArchambaud rode for France in the [[Tour de France]] between the wars. His sudden changes of form and frequent falls meant that he never won the race, but he did win nine stages<ref name=\"velo-club.net\"/>  and wear the [[yellow jersey]].\n\nHe won a shorter stage race, [[Paris\u2013Nice]], in 1936 and 1939.<ref>http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/cy/profiles/2357.html</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1932\n: [[Grand Prix des Nations]]: winner\n;1933\n: [[1933 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n:: Winner stages 1 and 11\n:: 5th overall\n:: 9 days in the [[yellow jersey]]\n;1935\n: [[1935 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stages 5A and 14B\n::7th overall\n: [[1935 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]:\n:: Winner stage 14B\n: Paris-Caen\n: [[Six-day racing|Six days]] of Paris\n:GP de l'Echo d'Alger\n;1936\n: [[1936 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 4\n::5 days in the yellow jersey.\n: [[Paris\u2013Nice]]\n;1937\n: [[1937 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 2\n: [[Hour record]]\n: [[Giro della provincia Milano]] (with [[Aldo Bini]])\n;1939\n: [[1939 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n:: Winner stages 10B, 10C, 12B and 17B\n: [[Paris\u2013Nice]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cycling Archives|282}}\n*{{Tour de France results|2638|archive=20070807135513}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frans Slaats]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Hour record|UCI hour record]] (45.767 km)| years = 3 November 1937-7 November 1942}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Fausto Coppi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Archambaud, Maurice}}\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:French Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:French Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_Archambaud"}
{"title_page": "No More Tears", "text_new": "{{About|the Ozzy Osbourne album}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = No More Tears\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n| cover      = Ozzy Osbourne - No More Tears.JPG\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Cover photography by [[Matt Mahurin]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1991|9|17|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 1989\u20131991\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Henson Recording Studios|A&M Studios]] and Devonshire Studios, Los Angeles, California\n| genre      =\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=57|s=2}}\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic Associated]]\n| producer   =\n* Duane Baron\n* [[John Purdell]]\n| prev_title = [[No Rest for the Wicked (Ozzy Osbourne album)|No Rest for the Wicked]]\n| prev_year  = 1988\n| next_title = [[Ozzmosis]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = No More Tears\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[No More Tears (Ozzy Osbourne song)|No More Tears]]\" / \"S.I.N.\n | single1date = 1 June 1991\n | single4     = [[Mama, I'm Coming Home]]\" / \"Don't Blame Me\n | single4date = 12 March 1992\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''No More Tears''''' is the sixth solo studio album by English [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] vocalist [[Ozzy Osbourne]]. Released on 17 September 1991, the album charted at number 17 on the [[UK Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"GB\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/19970/ozzy-osbourne/ |title=Ozzy Osbourne Official Charts |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=25 October 2015 }}</ref> and number seven on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart.<ref name=\"album\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-tears-mw0000675043/awards |title=No More Tears Billboard Albums |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref> ''No More Tears'' spawned four singles which reached the top ten of the US [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart, including the number two \"[[Mama, I'm Coming Home]]\",<ref name=\"singles\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-tears-mw0000675043/awards |title=No More Tears Billboard Singles |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref> and the [[36th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy-winning]] track \"I Don't Want to Change the World\".<ref name=\"award\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-tears-mw0000675043/awards |title=No More Tears Grammy Award |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref> Along with 1980's ''[[Blizzard of Ozz]]'' it is one of Osbourne's two best-selling solo albums in North America, having been certified [[RIAA certification|quadruple platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php |title=RIAA Searchable Database-Search: Ozzy Osbourne |accessdate=22 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626174049/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php |archivedate=26 June 2007 }}</ref> and [[Music Canada|double platinum]] by [[Canadian Recording Industry Association|CRIA]].<ref name=\"CRIA\" >{{cite web |url= https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?fwp_gp_search=ozzy%20osbourne |title=Gold Platinum Search for Ozzy Osbourne |publisher=[[Music Canada]] |accessdate=25 October 2015 }}</ref> It was Osbourne's final album to feature drummer [[Randy Castillo]] and longtime bassist and songwriter [[Bob Daisley]].\n\n== Background ==\nGuitarist [[Zakk Wylde]] contributed songwriting to the album, while [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] bassist/vocalist [[Lemmy|Lemmy Kilmister]] wrote the lyrics for six songs; however, only four were used on the album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zakk Wylde Interview|url= http://musiclegends.ca/interviews/zakk-wylde-interview/|publisher=Music Legends|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref> Although [[Mike Inez]] appeared in the album's [[Music video|videos]] and promotional tours, long-time Osbourne collaborator [[Bob Daisley]] plays bass on the entire album. Inez is credited as a writer for the title track; although he does not perform on the actual recording, the intro bass riff was composed by him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.classicrockrevisited.com/interviews02/Bob+Daisley+Interview.htm |title=Bob Daisley - The Interview |last=Wright |first=Jeb |publisher=Classic Rock Revisited.com |date=April 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516075317/http://www.classicrockrevisited.com/interviews02/Bob%2BDaisley%2BInterview.htm |archivedate=16 May 2007 |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe 2002 reissue of ''No More Tears'' featured two additional tracks entitled \"Don't Blame Me\" and \"Party with the Animals\". Both tracks had originally been released in 1991 as B-sides.\n\nAccording to professional wrestler and [[Fozzy]] lead vocalist [[Chris Jericho]], when asked about the title of the song \"A.V.H.\", Osbourne told him it stands for \"[[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] Highway\", an homage to the football team he and his [[Black Sabbath]] bandmates followed as young men growing up in [[Birmingham]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Jericho |first1=Chris |authorlink=Chris Jericho |last2=Fornatale |first2=Peter Thomas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hq2nAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT135&lpg=PT135&dq=chris+jericho+the+best+in+the+world+at+what+i+have+no+idea+Aston+Villa+Highway&source=bl&ots=LsG-9e6APB&sig=eNIBTFk3wFo8n8VTGHMEfoROWeQ&hl=it&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAWoVChMI6IyfsrGVyQIVQmEPCh25HAPs#v=onepage&q=chris%20jericho%20the%20best%20in%20the%20world%20at%20what%20i%20have%20no%20idea%20Aston%20Villa%20Highway&f=false |title=The Best in the World: At What I Have No Idea |location=London, UK |publisher=Gotham Books |date=14 October 2014 |isbn=978-1592407521 |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-tears-mw0000675043 |title=Ozzy Osbourne - No More Tears review |last=Ruhlmann |first=William |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2score = B+<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,315596,00.html|title=No More Tears Review|last=Garza|first=Janiss|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=20 September 1991|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n| noprose = yes\n}}\n''No More Tears'' received positive reviews from critics, and is considered to be one of Osbourne's best albums. ''[[Loudwire]]'' ranked the album #22 on their list of \"Top 90 Hard Rock + Metal Albums of the 90's\".<ref>https://loudwire.com/top-hard-rock-metal-albums-1990s/</ref> ''[[Ultimate Classic Rock]]'' included ''No More Tears'' on their list \"Top 100 90's Rock Albums\".<ref>https://ultimateclassicrock.com/90s-rock-albums/</ref> They also considered it to be Osbourne's third best album, only behind his first two albums.<ref>https://ultimateclassicrock.com/ozzy-osbourne-albums-ranked/</ref> ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' also considered it to be Osbourne's third best album.<ref>https://www.loudersound.com/features/ozzy-osbourne-solo-albums-ranked-from-worst-to-best</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Zakk Wylde]] and [[Randy Castillo]], except where noted\n| title1          = Mr. Tinkertrain\n| writer1         = \n| length1         = 5:57\n| title2          = [[I Don't Want to Change the World]]\n| writer2         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Castillo\n* [[Lemmy|Lemmy Kilmister]]\n}}\n| length2         = 4:06\n| title3          = [[Mama, I'm Coming Home]]\n| writer3         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Kilmister\n}}\n| length3         = 4:11\n| title4          = Desire\n| writer4         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Castillo\n* Kilmister\n}}\n| length4         = 5:46\n| title5          = [[No More Tears (Ozzy Osbourne song)|No More Tears]]\n| writer5         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Castillo\n* [[Mike Inez]]\n* [[John Purdell]]\n}}\n| length5         = 7:24\n| title6          = S.I.N.\n| writer6         =\n| length6         = 4:47\n| title7          = [[Hellraiser (song)|Hellraiser]]\n| writer7         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Kilmister\n}}\n| length7         = 4:52\n| title8          = Time After Time\n| writer8         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n}}\n| length8         = 4:20\n| title9          = Zombie Stomp\n| writer9         =\n| length9         = 6:14\n| title10         = A.V.H.\n| writer10        =\n| length10        = 4:13\n| title11         = Road to Nowhere\n| writer11        =\n| length11        = 5:11\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = 2002 reissue bonus tracks\n| title12         = Don't Blame Me\n| length12        = 5:06\n| title13         = Party with the Animals\n| length13        = 4:17\n| total_length    = 66:25\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]] \u2013 vocals\n* [[Zakk Wylde]] \u2013 guitars\n* [[Randy Castillo]] \u2013 drums \n* [[John Sinclair (musician)|John Sinclair]] \u2013 keyboards\n* [[Bob Daisley]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Mike Inez]] \u2013 bass/inspiration and musical direction (did not perform on album)\n\n'''Production'''\n\n* Duane Baron \u2013 producer, [[Audio engineer|engineer]]\n* [[John Purdell]] \u2013 producer, engineer\n* Michael Bosley \u2013 engineer\n* [[Michael Wagener]] \u2013 [[mixing engineer|mixing]]\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013 [[Mastering engineer|mastering]]\n\n'''2002 reissue information'''\n\n* Bruce Dickinson \u2013 reissue executive producer\n* Chris Athens \u2013 mastering at Sterling Sound\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}} \n{{col-break}}\n===Album===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" width=\"