oming+Home&cat=s|title=Ozzy Osbourne \u2013 Mama, I'm Coming Home |work=Austriancharts.at |publisher=[[Media Control Charts]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 |language= German }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|42\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[Swiss Hitparade|Swiss Singles Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://hitparade.ch/song/Ozzy-Osbourne/Mama,-I'm-Coming-Home-5469|title=Ozzy Osbourne \u2013 Mama, I'm Coming Home |work=Hitparade.ch |publisher=[[Media Control Charts]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 |language= German }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|62\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\"|1992\n|align=\"center\"|\"Time After Time\"\n|align=\"center\"| Mainstream Rock (USA)<ref name=\"singles\" />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\"Road to Nowhere\"\n|align=\"center\"| Mainstream Rock (USA)<ref name=\"singles\" />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\"Mr. Tinkertrain\"\n|align=\"center\"| Mainstream Rock (USA)<ref name=\"singles\" />\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|34\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Certifications ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n|+ Certifications\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Country\n! scope=\"col\" |Organization\n! scope=\"col\" |Year\n! scope=\"col\" |Sales\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |USA\n|[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]\n|2000\n|4\u00d7 Platinum (+ 4,000,000)<ref name=\"RIAA\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |Canada\n|[[Music Canada|CRIA]]\n|1992\n|2\u00d7 Platinum (+ 200,000)<ref name=\"CRIA\" /> \n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Ozzy Osbourne}}\n\n[[Category:Ozzy Osbourne albums]]\n[[Category:1991 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Purdell]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Duane Baron]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at A&M Studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Ozzy Osbourne album}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = No More Tears\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n| cover      = Ozzy Osbourne - No More Tears.JPG\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Cover photography by [[Matt Mahurin]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1991|9|17|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 1989\u20131991\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Henson Recording Studios|A&M Studios]] and Devonshire Studios, Los Angeles, California\n| genre      =\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=57|s=2}}\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic Associated]]\n| producer   =\n* Duane Baron\n* [[John Purdell]]\n| prev_title = [[No Rest for the Wicked (Ozzy Osbourne album)|No Rest for the Wicked]]\n| prev_year  = 1988\n| next_title = [[Ozzmosis]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = No More Tears\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[No More Tears (Ozzy Osbourne song)|No More Tears]]\" / \"S.I.N.\n | single1date = 1 June 1991\n | single4     = [[Mama, I'm Coming Home]]\" / \"Don't Blame Me\n | single4date = 12 March 1992\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''No More Tears''''' is the sixth solo studio album by English [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] vocalist [[Ozzy Osbourne]]. Released on 17 September 1991, the album charted at number 17 on the [[UK Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"GB\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/19970/ozzy-osbourne/ |title=Ozzy Osbourne Official Charts |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=25 October 2015 }}</ref> and number seven on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart.<ref name=\"album\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-tears-mw0000675043/awards |title=No More Tears Billboard Albums |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref> ''No More Tears'' spawned four singles which reached the top ten of the US [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart, including the number two \"[[Mama, I'm Coming Home]]\",<ref name=\"singles\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-tears-mw0000675043/awards |title=No More Tears Billboard Singles |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref> and the [[36th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy-winning]] track \"I Don't Want to Change the World\".<ref name=\"award\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-tears-mw0000675043/awards |title=No More Tears Grammy Award |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref> Along with 1980's ''[[Blizzard of Ozz]]'' it is one of Osbourne's two best-selling solo albums in North America, having been certified [[RIAA certification|quadruple platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php |title=RIAA Searchable Database-Search: Ozzy Osbourne |accessdate=22 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626174049/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php |archivedate=26 June 2007 }}</ref> and [[Music Canada|double platinum]] by [[Canadian Recording Industry Association|CRIA]].<ref name=\"CRIA\" >{{cite web |url= https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?fwp_gp_search=ozzy%20osbourne |title=Gold Platinum Search for Ozzy Osbourne |publisher=[[Music Canada]] |accessdate=25 October 2015 }}</ref> It was Osbourne's final album to feature drummer [[Randy Castillo]] and longtime bassist and songwriter [[Bob Daisley]].\n\n== Background ==\nGuitarist [[Zakk Wylde]] contributed songwriting to the album, while [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] bassist/vocalist [[Lemmy|Lemmy Kilmister]] wrote the lyrics for six songs; however, only four were used on the album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zakk Wylde Interview|url= http://musiclegends.ca/interviews/zakk-wylde-interview/|publisher=Music Legends|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref> Although [[Mike Inez]] appeared in the album's [[Music video|videos]] and promotional tours, long-time Osbourne collaborator [[Bob Daisley]] plays bass on the entire album. Inez is credited as a writer for the title track; although he does not perform on the actual recording, the intro bass riff was composed by him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.classicrockrevisited.com/interviews02/Bob+Daisley+Interview.htm |title=Bob Daisley - The Interview |last=Wright |first=Jeb |publisher=Classic Rock Revisited.com |date=April 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516075317/http://www.classicrockrevisited.com/interviews02/Bob%2BDaisley%2BInterview.htm |archivedate=16 May 2007 |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe 2002 reissue of ''No More Tears'' featured two additional tracks entitled \"Don't Blame Me\" and \"Party with the Animals\". Both tracks had originally been released in 1991 as B-sides.\n\nAccording to professional wrestler and [[Fozzy]] lead vocalist [[Chris Jericho]], when asked about the title of the song \"A.V.H.\", Osbourne told him it stands for \"[[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] Highway\", an homage to the football team he and his [[Black Sabbath]] bandmates followed as young men growing up in [[Birmingham]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Jericho |first1=Chris |authorlink=Chris Jericho |last2=Fornatale |first2=Peter Thomas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hq2nAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT135&lpg=PT135&dq=chris+jericho+the+best+in+the+world+at+what+i+have+no+idea+Aston+Villa+Highway&source=bl&ots=LsG-9e6APB&sig=eNIBTFk3wFo8n8VTGHMEfoROWeQ&hl=it&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAWoVChMI6IyfsrGVyQIVQmEPCh25HAPs#v=onepage&q=chris%20jericho%20the%20best%20in%20the%20world%20at%20what%20i%20have%20no%20idea%20Aston%20Villa%20Highway&f=false |title=The Best in the World: At What I Have No Idea |location=London, UK |publisher=Gotham Books |date=14 October 2014 |isbn=978-1592407521 |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-tears-mw0000675043 |title=Ozzy Osbourne - No More Tears review |last=Ruhlmann |first=William |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=16 November 2015 }}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2score = B+<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,315596,00.html|title=No More Tears Review|last=Garza|first=Janiss|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=20 September 1991|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n| noprose = yes\n}}\n''No More Tears'' received positive reviews from critics, and is considered to be one of Osbourne's best albums. ''[[Loudwire]]'' ranked the album #22 on their list \"Top 90 Hard Rock + Metal Albums of the 90's\".<ref>https://loudwire.com/top-hard-rock-metal-albums-1990s/</ref> ''[[Ultimate Classic Rock]]'' included ''No More Tears'' on their list \"Top 100 90's Rock Albums\".<ref>https://ultimateclassicrock.com/90s-rock-albums/</ref> They also considered it to be Osbourne's third best album, only behind his first two albums.<ref>https://ultimateclassicrock.com/ozzy-osbourne-albums-ranked/</ref> ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' also considered it to be Osbourne's third best album.<ref>https://www.loudersound.com/features/ozzy-osbourne-solo-albums-ranked-from-worst-to-best</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Zakk Wylde]] and [[Randy Castillo]], except where noted\n| title1          = Mr. Tinkertrain\n| writer1         = \n| length1         = 5:57\n| title2          = [[I Don't Want to Change the World]]\n| writer2         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Castillo\n* [[Lemmy|Lemmy Kilmister]]\n}}\n| length2         = 4:06\n| title3          = [[Mama, I'm Coming Home]]\n| writer3         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Kilmister\n}}\n| length3         = 4:11\n| title4          = Desire\n| writer4         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Castillo\n* Kilmister\n}}\n| length4         = 5:46\n| title5          = [[No More Tears (Ozzy Osbourne song)|No More Tears]]\n| writer5         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Castillo\n* [[Mike Inez]]\n* [[John Purdell]]\n}}\n| length5         = 7:24\n| title6          = S.I.N.\n| writer6         =\n| length6         = 4:47\n| title7          = [[Hellraiser (song)|Hellraiser]]\n| writer7         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n* Kilmister\n}}\n| length7         = 4:52\n| title8          = Time After Time\n| writer8         = {{flatlist|\n* Osbourne\n* Wylde\n}}\n| length8         = 4:20\n| title9          = Zombie Stomp\n| writer9         =\n| length9         = 6:14\n| title10         = A.V.H.\n| writer10        =\n| length10        = 4:13\n| title11         = Road to Nowhere\n| writer11        =\n| length11        = 5:11\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = 2002 reissue bonus tracks\n| title12         = Don't Blame Me\n| length12        = 5:06\n| title13         = Party with the Animals\n| length13        = 4:17\n| total_length    = 66:25\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]] \u2013 vocals\n* [[Zakk Wylde]] \u2013 guitars\n* [[Randy Castillo]] \u2013 drums \n* [[John Sinclair (musician)|John Sinclair]] \u2013 keyboards\n* [[Bob Daisley]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Mike Inez]] \u2013 bass/inspiration and musical direction (did not perform on album)\n\n'''Production'''\n\n* Duane Baron \u2013 producer, [[Audio engineer|engineer]]\n* [[John Purdell]] \u2013 producer, engineer\n* Michael Bosley \u2013 engineer\n* [[Michael Wagener]] \u2013 [[mixing engineer|mixing]]\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013 [[Mastering engineer|mastering]]\n\n'''2002 reissue information'''\n\n* Bruce Dickinson \u2013 reissue executive producer\n* Chris Athens \u2013 mastering at Sterling Sound\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}} \n{{col-break}}\n===Album===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" width=\"330px\"\n!align=\"center\"|Year\n!align=\"center\"|Chart\n!align=\"center\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"8\"|1991\n|align=\"center\"|[[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] (USA)<ref name=\"album\" /> \n|align=\"center\"|7\n|- \n|align=\"center\"|[[VG-li